    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (78.36) leading the charge as our most lethal weapon. His matchup against McCullers Jr. is quintessential for our strategy; not only does the SP benefit from a high xERA, but McCullers Jr.\u2019s deliberate pace provides **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** with an elite environment to weaponize his sprint speed on the basepaths. Similarly, **Trevor Story** (75.93) is a core start today, as the combination of a favorable matchup against Young and a distinct park-factor boost vaults him into the top tier of our offensive output. While **James Wood** (73.18) faces the lefty Hudson, his premium spot at the top of the order ensures enough high-leverage opportunities to warrant a strong start despite the neutral platoon dynamic.\n\nWe are navigating a treacherous pitching environment elsewhere, specifically with **Brice Turang** (49.29) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (47.90), both of whom are facing elite arms in Skenes and Eovaldi, respectively. **Brice Turang** remains in the lineup purely for his table-setting role and stolen base utility, though his efficiency score is suppressed by Skenes\u2019s dominance and a high-caliber opposing catcher. The most difficult bench decision involved **Seiya Suzuki** (45.02); while he hovered near the cutoff, the uncertainty surrounding his lineup spot\u2014coupled with a brutal matchup against Sheehan\u2014kept him on the pine in favor of the more stable efficiency metrics offered by **Giancarlo Stanton** (64.64), who benefits significantly from the soft landing provided by the matchup against McCullers Jr. \n\nCaution is advised regarding **Jose Caballero** (56.31); while his raw score is passable, his presence at the bottom of the order and a negative platoon split against McCullers Jr. make him a volatile asset today. We are monitoring **Alex Freeland** (47.84) closely, as his utility slot assignment is the thin line between a productive day and a wasted roster spot. With **Vinnie Pasquantino**, **Corbin Carroll**, and others currently sidelined or excluded from the primary lineup, our margin for error is razor-thin. We rely on the speed-weighted projections of **Mickey Moniak** (64.12) to offset the potential drag caused by the tough matchups faced by **Austin Riley** (63.37) and **Josh Naylor** (67.25) against mid-tier arms.",
